Minor semantics. Notes is an application platform/framework with available
development tools.  Notes isnt a language per se but an application framework
providing many tools that allow developers to build applications in the
language of their choice, allowing for very complex multiplatform mission
critical solutions to be generated with relative ease.

Java is a restricted subset of C++, with some bells and whistles.  HotJava is
the "browser" technology for Java, basically an interpreter.

Java has major restrictions on filesystem access, forking, resource usage, etc.
(eg Java is living in an effectively insecure framework and cannot be a trusted
application development/execution environment until some real security comes to
the net... wide spread kereboros is a great idea).

Java has been hyped as the greatest thing since sliced bread.  It is
interesting, cute even.  Useful?  Only time will tell.  Animated Icons dont do
anything for me.  The server push (hit ctrl-alt-f under netscape) already works
in some html browsers btw, and Java really adds nothing there.

>
> >As for Java...  why would anyone want to build an application on an
> >interpreted language?
>
> Well, Visual Basic is interpreted.  Most of the client/server type tools
> (PowerBuilder and the like) are also interpreted.  More importantly,

...in the same vein as Quickbasic "interpreted".  As the application is loaded,
it is transformed (one line at a time) into a p/i-code intermediate level
language that does NOT need to be interpreted when run.  This is the way
quick basic, VB, et al work.

> however, is that a Java bytestream is also portable across platforms,
> from PDAs to workstations.  And, if speed is an issue, the bytestream can
> be compiled into native code, provided your Java interpreter supports it.

Which is precisely my point.  In order to get a fast app where one is needed,
you need to compile the code.  Speed is always an issue.

>
> >Never mind the bandwidth issues (which will initially strangle it),
