Kinda defeats the purpose of it, eh?

>
> >The hype surrounding this is monumental and silly... it is a solution in
> >search of a problem which doesnt exist.  Apart from spinning globes it has
> >limited utility.
>
> It appears someone's suffering from a severe lack of imagination. :)
> Java is a language, and you can build just about anything in it, provided
> it isn't tied to a specific platform.

Some people suffer from grandiose imaginations :-) and some from quite realistic
expectations.  The hype surrounding Java is almost as bad as that around the
win95 situation.

Java is a language.  In order to address the issue of security, Java was
properly crippled (filesystem, etc) until such a time as real network security
exists, and apps can be authenticated.  In fact what you can do with java is
quite limited, and hence my point.

If Java wants to be useful, address the security issue first and SOLVE it.  Then
Java would be beneficial.

>
> >VRML solved a problem.  Java/Hot Java dosent.
>
> Is this really your opinion, or is this coming about because you work for
> SGI and not for SUN? :)

VRML is based upon the Open Inventor spec, which as the name implies, is Open.
Java is not an open spec (please correct me if I am wrong about this and there
is a multivendor councel proposing Java 2.0).  VRML was designed IN THE PUBLIC
DOMAIN, to address the problem of not having 3D viewing capabilities on web
pages.  3D capabilities are very important to some industries (most actually),
and the introduction of VRML helped to solve some significant problems.  Now
VRML 2.0 is being designed (NOT by SGI alone, but in consortium).

What problem does Java address?  The need for a downloadable spreadsheet?  A
spinning globe?  The server push?

Your assumption about my motives is incorrect.  I see no problem solved by Java
that needs solving.

Java is cute technology of marginal utility, and it certainly doesnt warrant the
attention it has been getting, mostly because the idea is great and the
implementation is flawed (mostly due to the lack of network
security/authentication services), which is NOT Java's fault.  The underlying
technology just isnt ready for it.

If you are on a closed firewalled system, then you ARE going to want file system
access etc, not included in Java.  Oh well...

As I said, at the moment it is a solution in search of a problem.

